

Ask for exceptional service

When I joined SCG (Spectrum Capital Group), another acronym to express my heart – Serving Christ Graciously, a gentle reminder that we are to work unto the Lord, as if He is our client, boss, partner and co-worker. Whether you are buying and/or selling, expect exceptional service – response to your concerns, staying ahead of the process, anticipating the next turn, understanding the critical path – sealing the deal as you seal up your moving boxes!
h

Ask for expert advice

I will do a qualified appraisal, suggest quick staging fixes, and quiz you about your financial goals to ensure confidence about the decisions you will soon be required to make as you navigate your quest for a solid future.
U

Ask for excellent property analysis

I have a practical eye, seeing property benefits, potential and possible “road bumps”. Let me take you on a tour of your next property preview to see if there are any “blindspots”, so you can buy with confidence.
U

Consider changing the focus keywords to something unique.";s:9:"more_info";s:1145:" Whilst duplicate content isn't technically penalized it presents three rather niggly issues for search engines:

1. It's unclear which versions to include/exclude from their indexes.
2. They don't know whether to direct the link metrics (trust, authority, anchor text, link equity, etc.) to one page, or keep it separated between multiple versions.
3. The engine is unsure which version to rank for query results.

So whilst there's no direct penalty, if your content isn't unique then search engine algorithms could be filtering out your articles from their results. The easiest way to make sure this doesn't happen is to try and make each of your posts and pages as unique as possible, hence specifying different focus keywords for each article you write.

Note: If you happen to have two pages with the same content, it's important to tell search engines which one to show in search results using the Canonical URL feature. You can read more about this here. ";s:10:"status_msg";s:42:"You haven't used this focus keyword before";}}}

post_content:
This is an example page. It's different from a blog post because it will stay in one place and will show up in your site navigation (in most themes). Most people start with an About page that introduces them to potential site visitors. It might say something like this:

Hi there! I'm a bike messenger by day, aspiring actor by night, and this is my website. I live in Los Angeles, have a great dog named Jack, and I like piña coladas. (And gettin' caught in the rain.)

...or something like this:

The XYZ Doohickey Company was founded in 1971, and has been providing quality doohickeys to the public ever since. Located in Gotham City, XYZ employs over 2,000 people and does all kinds of awesome things for the Gotham community.

As a new WordPress user, you should go to your dashboard to delete this page and create new pages for your content. Have fun!
post_title: Sample Page

So whilst there's no direct penalty, if your content isn't unique then search engine algorithms could be filtering out your articles from their results. The easiest way to make sure this doesn't happen is to try and make each of your posts and pages as unique as possible, hence specifying different focus keywords for each article you write.

Consider changing the focus keywords to something unique.";s:9:"more_info";s:1145:" Whilst duplicate content isn't technically penalized it presents three rather niggly issues for search engines:

1. It's unclear which versions to include/exclude from their indexes.
2. They don't know whether to direct the link metrics (trust, authority, anchor text, link equity, etc.) to one page, or keep it separated between multiple versions.
3. The engine is unsure which version to rank for query results.

So whilst there's no direct penalty, if your content isn't unique then search engine algorithms could be filtering out your articles from their results. The easiest way to make sure this doesn't happen is to try and make each of your posts and pages as unique as possible, hence specifying different focus keywords for each article you write.

1. It's unclear which versions to include/exclude from their indexes.

3. The engine is unsure which version to rank for query results.

The easiest way to make sure this doesn't happen is to try and make each of your posts and pages as unique as possible, hence specifying different focus keywords for each article you write.

1. It's unclear which versions to include/exclude from their indexes.
2. They don't know whether to direct the link metrics (trust, authority, anchor text, link equity, etc.) to one page, or keep it separated between multiple versions.
3. The engine is unsure which version to rank for query results.

So whilst there's no direct penalty, if your content isn't unique then search engine algorithms could be filtering out your articles from their results. The easiest way to make sure this doesn't happen is to try and make each of your posts and pages as unique as possible, hence specifying different focus keywords for each article you write.

Note: If you happen to have two pages with the same content, it's important to tell search engines which one to show in search results using the Canonical URL feature. You can read more about this here. ";s:10:"status_msg";s:42:"You haven't used this focus keyword before";}}}

View the market report

[/et_pb_slide][et_pb_slide heading="Condo construction shows gains" button_text="Read More" button_link="https://eyeonhousing.org/2022/05/condo-construction-market-showing-gains/" url_new_window="on" _builder_version="4.18.0" _module_preset="default" global_colors_info="{}" sticky_transition="on"]

Source: National Assn. of Homebuilders
Just as townhome demand is rising so is condo demand. The first quarter was the best quarter for condo construction since the third quarter of 2008 — in about 14 years, according to the National Association of Home Builders.

As buyers search for greater affordability, they may be drawn to condos. Still, the median existing condo and co-op sales price was $340,000 in April, an increase of 13.1% compared to a year earlier, according to the National Association of REALTORS®. But for comparison, the median existing single-family home price was $397,600 in April, up 14.8% annually.

[/et_pb_slide][et_pb_slide heading="Hot market could offer hope for buyers, sellers" button_text="Read More" button_link="https://www.realtor.com/news/trends/the-red-hot-u-s-housing-market-finally-offers-hope-for-buyers-and-sellers/" url_new_window="on" _builder_version="4.18.0" _module_preset="default" link_option_url_new_window="on" global_colors_info="{}" sticky_transition="on"]

Source: MarketWatch
Double-digit home price increases compared to last year and rising interest rates are dampening housing affordability by raising the average monthly payment 50% more than a year ago. Those rising costs are sidelining more hopeful home buyers.

But there are signs that the housing market could be slowing, which could put less pressure on home prices and offer hope for home sellers and buyers. For the fourth straight month, sales of new homes dropped, reaching their lowest level since the pandemic. Existing-home sales also decreased in April, falling for the third consecutive month and down nearly 6% compared to a year ago, according to National Assn. of REALTORS® data. The drop in sales could offer less competition to buyers who are eager to jump in but keep getting beat out.

[/et_pb_slide][et_pb_slide heading="New home sales drop in April" button_text="Read More" button_link="https://money.yahoo.com/new-home-sales-plunge-cooling-housing-market-154050122.html?guccounter=1" url_new_window="on" _builder_version="4.18.0" _module_preset="default" global_colors_info="{}" sticky_transition="on"]

Source: National Assn. of Homebuilders
New home sales, which gained favor with many would-be buyers over the past two years due to the shortage of existing homes for sale, dropped for the fourth straight month in April, offering up another sign that the housing market is starting to slow.

The volume of new single‐family home sale fell to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 591,000 last month, according to the Census Bureau and the Department of Housing and Urban Development, down 16.6% from the March rate and 26.9% lower than the rate a year ago.

[/et_pb_slide][et_pb_slide heading="Homeowners accumulated more than $240,000 in equity over 10 years" button_text="Read More" button_link="https://www.nar.realtor/blogs/economists-outlook/metro-wealth-reports-as-of-2022-q1" url_new_window="on" _builder_version="4.18.0" _module_preset="default" global_colors_info="{}" sticky_transition="on"]

Source: National Assn. of REALTORS®
As prices climb, homeowners who’ve owned their homes for a while have seen a boost in appreciation over the past decade. Homeowners in San Jose-Sunnyvale-Santa Clara, Calif.; San Francisco-Oakland-Hayward, Calif.; Anaheim-Santa Ana-Irvine, Calif.; and urban Honolulu, Hawaii built up the largest amount of home equity.

A homeowner who purchased a single-family existing home 10 years ago would have gained $229,400 in home equity if the home were sold at the median price in the fourth quarter of 2021, according to analysis by the National Association of REALTORS®. In the past five years, home prices have risen at an annual pace of nearly 10%, NAR reports. A homeowner who purchased a typical home five years ago would have gained $125,300 from just price appreciation alone.

[/et_pb_slide][et_pb_slide heading="Sellers rush before market slows" button_text="Read More" button_link="https://www.cnbc.com/2022/05/26/home-listings-suddenly-spike-as-sellers-worry-theyll-miss-out-on-red-hot-market.html" url_new_window="on" _builder_version="4.18.0" _module_preset="default" global_colors_info="{}" sticky_transition="on"]

Source: CNBC
As signs of a slowing real estate market are growing across the country — both existing-home sales and new-home sales are falling — home sellers are growing concerned that they could miss out on the buyer frenzy. With the market shifting, home sellers are in a hurry to find a buyer before demand weakens further

The inventory of homes for sale rose 9% last week compared to a year ago, according to Realtor.com®. New listings are rising nearly twice as fast in the past four weeks as they did a year ago.

[/et_pb_slide][et_pb_slide heading="Mortgage rates east but demand declines" button_text="Read More" button_link="https://www.cnbc.com/2022/06/01/mortgage-demand-falls-to-lowest-level-since-2018-even-as-interest-rates-ease.html" url_new_window="on" _builder_version="4.18.0" _module_preset="default" global_colors_info="{}" sticky_transition="on"]

Source: CNBC
Even after rates declined slightly last week, mortgage demand slipped to the lowest level since December 2018, according to the Mortgage Bankers Association. Despite a slight decline, mortgage rates are significantly higher than they were at the start of this year.

The average contract interest rate for 30-year fixed-rate mortgages with conforming loan balances decreased to 5.33% from 5.46% with points dropping to 0.51 from 0.60 for loans with a 20% down payment. Applications for a mortgage to purchase a home fell 1% last week compared with the previous week. Volume was 14% lower than the same week one year ago.

[/et_pb_slide][et_pb_slide heading="Housing market predictions for 2022: Rates, prices, and inventory" button_text="Click Here" button_link="https://themortgagereports.com/85263/housing-market-predictions-2022" _builder_version="4.17.4" _module_preset="default" link_option_url="https://themortgagereports.com/85263/housing-market-predictions-2022" global_colors_info="{}" sticky_transition="on"]

The 2021 housing market was a tough one for home shoppers.

Low rates and increased flexibility from working remotely put many first-time homebuyers on the map. But limited inventory, skyrocketing prices, and fierce bidding wars made housing harder to come by.

But things may soon level out to a more â€˜normalizedâ€™ market, according to real estate experts. We could see competition start to taper off and price growth begin to moderate.

In short, 2022 should be a better market for buyers.

Market Report

Condo construction shows gains

Source: National Assn. of HomebuildersJust as townhome demand is rising so is condo demand. The first quarter was the best quarter for condo construction since the third quarter of 2008 — in about 14 years, according to the National Association of Home Builders.
As buyers search for greater affordability, they may be drawn to condos. Still, the median existing condo and co-op sales price was $340,000 in April, an increase of 13.1% compared to a year earlier, according to the National Association of REALTORS®. But for comparison, the median existing single-family home price was $397,600 in April, up 14.8% annually.
Read More

Hot market could offer hope for buyers, sellers

Source: MarketWatchDouble-digit home price increases compared to last year and rising interest rates are dampening housing affordability by raising the average monthly payment 50% more than a year ago. Those rising costs are sidelining more hopeful home buyers.
But there are signs that the housing market could be slowing, which could put less pressure on home prices and offer hope for home sellers and buyers. For the fourth straight month, sales of new homes dropped, reaching their lowest level since the pandemic. Existing-home sales also decreased in April, falling for the third consecutive month and down nearly 6% compared to a year ago, according to National Assn. of REALTORS® data. The drop in sales could offer less competition to buyers who are eager to jump in but keep getting beat out.
Read More

New home sales drop in April

Source: National Assn. of HomebuildersNew home sales, which gained favor with many would-be buyers over the past two years due to the shortage of existing homes for sale, dropped for the fourth straight month in April, offering up another sign that the housing market is starting to slow.
The volume of new single‐family home sale fell to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 591,000 last month, according to the Census Bureau and the Department of Housing and Urban Development, down 16.6% from the March rate and 26.9% lower than the rate a year ago.
Read More

Homeowners accumulated more than $240,000 in equity over 10 years

Source: National Assn. of REALTORS®As prices climb, homeowners who’ve owned their homes for a while have seen a boost in appreciation over the past decade. Homeowners in San Jose-Sunnyvale-Santa Clara, Calif.; San Francisco-Oakland-Hayward, Calif.; Anaheim-Santa Ana-Irvine, Calif.; and urban Honolulu, Hawaii built up the largest amount of home equity.
A homeowner who purchased a single-family existing home 10 years ago would have gained $229,400 in home equity if the home were sold at the median price in the fourth quarter of 2021, according to analysis by the National Association of REALTORS®. In the past five years, home prices have risen at an annual pace of nearly 10%, NAR reports. A homeowner who purchased a typical home five years ago would have gained $125,300 from just price appreciation alone.
Read More

Sellers rush before market slows

Source: CNBCAs signs of a slowing real estate market are growing across the country — both existing-home sales and new-home sales are falling — home sellers are growing concerned that they could miss out on the buyer frenzy. With the market shifting, home sellers are in a hurry to find a buyer before demand weakens further
The inventory of homes for sale rose 9% last week compared to a year ago, according to Realtor.com®. New listings are rising nearly twice as fast in the past four weeks as they did a year ago.
Read More

Mortgage rates east but demand declines

Source: CNBCEven after rates declined slightly last week, mortgage demand slipped to the lowest level since December 2018, according to the Mortgage Bankers Association. Despite a slight decline, mortgage rates are significantly higher than they were at the start of this year.
The average contract interest rate for 30-year fixed-rate mortgages with conforming loan balances decreased to 5.33% from 5.46% with points dropping to 0.51 from 0.60 for loans with a 20% down payment. Applications for a mortgage to purchase a home fell 1% last week compared with the previous week. Volume was 14% lower than the same week one year ago.
Read More

Housing market predictions for 2022: Rates, prices, and inventory

The 2021 housing market was a tough one for home shoppers.
Low rates and increased flexibility from working remotely put many first-time homebuyers on the map. But limited inventory, skyrocketing prices, and fierce bidding wars made housing harder to come by.
But things may soon level out to a more â€˜normalizedâ€™ market, according to real estate experts. We could see competition start to taper off and price growth begin to moderate.
In short, 2022 should be a better market for buyers.

1. It's unclear which versions to include/exclude from their indexes.
2. They don't know whether to direct the link metrics (trust, authority, anchor text, link equity, etc.) to one page, or keep it separated between multiple versions.
3. The engine is unsure which version to rank for query results.

So whilst there's no direct penalty, if your content isn't unique then search engine algorithms could be filtering out your articles from their results. The easiest way to make sure this doesn't happen is to try and make each of your posts and pages as unique as possible, hence specifying different focus keywords for each article you write.
